A **Service Worker** is a **special type of JavaScript file** that runs **in the background**, separate from the main browser thread, and acts as a **proxy between your web application, the browser, and the network**.

Its main purpose is to enable **offline support, caching, background tasks, and performance improvements** for web apps.

***

## ✅ Simple Definition (Interview‑Ready)

> **A Service Worker is a background script that intercepts network requests and enables features like offline access, caching, push notifications, and background sync in web applications.**

***

## ✅ Why Service Workers Exist

Traditional web apps:

*   ❌ Need internet all the time
*   ❌ Lose data when network drops
*   ❌ Are slower on repeat visits

Service Workers solve this by:
✅ Caching resources  
✅ Working offline  
✅ Improving performance  
✅ Enabling PWA features

***

## ✅ What Can a Service Worker Do?

✔ Intercept HTTP requests  
✔ Cache API responses & assets  
✔ Serve content offline  
✔ Handle push notifications  
✔ Run background sync tasks  
✔ Improve loading speed

***

## ✅ What a Service Worker CANNOT Do

❌ Access DOM directly  
❌ Use `window`, `document`, `localStorage`  
❌ Block the UI thread

✅ It communicates with pages via **postMessage**

***

## ✅ Where Does a Service Worker Run?

```text
Web Page (UI)
   ↓
Service Worker (Background)
   ↓
Network / Cache / APIs
```

✅ Runs **even when the web page is closed** (within limits)

***

## ✅ Key Characteristics

| Feature            | Description               |
| ------------------ | ------------------------- |
| Runs in background | Separate from UI thread   |
| Event‑driven       | Wakes up only when needed |
| Requires HTTPS     | For security              |
| No DOM access      | Better performance        |
| Acts as proxy      | Between app & network     |

***

## ✅ Service Worker Lifecycle (VERY IMPORTANT)

Service workers have a **strict lifecycle**:

### 1️⃣ **Register**

```js
navigator.serviceWorker.register("/sw.js");
```

### 2️⃣ **Install**

*   Cache static assets

### 3️⃣ **Activate**

*   Clean old caches

### 4️⃣ **Fetch**

*   Intercept requests

***

## ✅ Example: Registering a Service Worker

```js
if ("serviceWorker" in navigator) {
  navigator.serviceWorker
    .register("/sw.js")
    .then(() => console.log("Service Worker registered"))
    .catch(err => console.error(err));
}
```

✅ Usually done in `index.js` or main entry file

***

## ✅ Basic Service Worker Example (`sw.js`)

### ✅ Install Event (Cache Files)

```js
self.addEventListener("install", event => {
  event.waitUntil(
    caches.open("app-cache").then(cache => {
      return cache.addAll([
        "/",
        "/index.html",
        "/styles.css",
        "/app.js"
      ]);
    })
  );
});
```

***

### ✅ Fetch Event (Serve from Cache)

```js
self.addEventListener("fetch", event => {
  event.respondWith(
    caches.match(event.request).then(response => {
      return response || fetch(event.request);
    })
  );
});
```

✅ Enables **offline support**

***

